PSEUDOCODE
==========

Enable clock for GPIOA and GPIOC
Configure PA5  as output (push-pull) - LED
Configure PC13 as input with pull-up - Button
Loop forever:
    If PC13 reads LOW (button pressed):
        Wait ~10ms (debounce)
        If PC13 still LOW:
            Toggle LED
            Wait until button is released

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA5   =>  Onboard LED (LD4) - Active HIGH
PC13  =>  Onboard User Button - Active LOW (pressed = 0)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY REGISTERS
=============

RCC (Reset and Clock Control)
|-------------|----------------|--------------------------|
| Register    | Field          | Description              |
|-------------|----------------|--------------------------|
| RCC->IOPENR | IOPCEN (bit 2) | Enables clock for GPIOC. |
|-------------|----------------|--------------------------|

GPIOC (General-Purpose Input/Output Port C)
|--------------|----------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register     | Field                | Description                                                                              |
|--------------|----------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| GPIOC->MODER | bits[27:26] for PC13 | 00 = Input Mode.This is actually the reset default for most pins, but set it explicitly. |
| GPIOC->PUPDR | bits[27:26] for PC13 | 01 = Pull-up enabled. Keeps the line HIGH when button is not pressed.                    |
| GPIOC->IDR   | bit 13               | Input Data Register. Read this bit to know the current state of PC13.                    |
|--------------|----------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* Forgetting the button is Active LOW - PC13 reads 0 when pressed, 1 when
  released. The onboard button connects PC13 to GND when pressed. If we check
  IDR & (1 << 13) without the !, our logic is inverted.

* No debounce = multiple triggers per press, Mechanical buttons bounce
  electrically for anywhere between 5–50ms on contact. Without the re-check
  after a small delay, one physical press can register as 5–20 presses. Always
  debounce.

* Skipping the release wait, If we toggle on press but don't wait for release,
  holding the button down will cause the LED to toggle rapidly on every loop
  iteration. The while (!(IDR & (1 << 13))) blocks until the finger lifts.

* Pull-up vs external resistor, The Nucleo board has an external pull-up on PC13
  already, so the internal pull-up here is redundant but harmless. On custom
  boards with a floating input pin and no pull-up, we will read garbage. Always
  know the hardware.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* Why ODR ^= here but BSRR in Program 1; Toggle (^=) on ODR is genuinely the
  cleanest way to flip a pin state without tracking it separately. It's a
  trade-off: fine in polling main loop, but unsafe inside an ISR where a context
  switch mid read-modify-write could corrupt state.

* PC13 quirk on Nucleo boards, On some Nucleo variants, PC13 is also connected
  to an RTC tamper/wakeup line. It works fine as GPIO input, but be aware if we
  later enable RTC, there can be conflicts.

* Polling is simple but burns CPU, This entire while(1) loop does nothing but
  check a pin repeatedly. At 16MHz that's millions of wasted checks per
  second. This is the motivation for EXTI interrupts, where the CPU is free to
  do other things and only reacts when the pin actually changes.

